
Robots in Society


September 2022



















ABSTRACT—From the moment of his existence, human has made many inventions to make his/her life easier.
    These were inventions that met basic needs such as hunting, feeding and protection in pre-archaeological histories; The invention of a sharp tool has enabled the exploration of different dimensions of hunting and has made it possible to meet nutritional needs more quickly and easily. The need for heating was eliminated with the invention of fire. These inventions have led people to other inventions. Agriculture, production and trade started with the inventions of the wheel and the water transport channel. Although these were the simplest and most primitive examples, people continued to produce inventions that served them. Thus, they gained both time and experience to meet different needs, even to philosophize!
    When we look at the science of Robotics, which is defined as the science that covers the studies on the preparation of systems that can help people on the other hand It is believed that it can completely replace human beings for some tasks. 
    The entry of machines into our lives and their increasing functions have spread over a long period of time. Although the automatic machines of Ebu'l Iz El Cezari, who is called the father of cybernetics living in the 13th century [1] he is not well known, the word robot was first used in "R.U.R." written by Karel Čapek in 1920. and It took place in  Rossum's Universal Robots game and then started to be used all over the world.
    When robots are mentioned in society, the first thing that comes to mind is that it is human-like beings. however, robot studies continue to exist in industrial, operational, medical and health fields, cybernetics, hobby and entertainment sector and military field and take up rapidly more space in our lives.
    This study has been prepared to provide a general overview of the subject, based on the fact that there are different views and concerns about the advantages and disadvantages of the use of robots in society.

Key Words—Robotics, Use of robots in society, Automation, .











    I. INTRODUCTION

    Long before the ancient times when robot-like things were imagined; with the beginning of human existence, many inventions have been produced that facilitate, organize and improve daily life. Every invention produced has served to be a part of the next evolution and to facilitate human life.
    This automation process, which human discovered for his/her own benefit was first expressed by Aristotle in the 4th century that 'the managers would not need staff if every tolls could do its own job.' with these words, it can be seen that people imagine a being that will help and serve him/her from the very beginning of his/her existence [2].
    In the BC 300, engineers created water-powered automations in this automation process, the definition of automation mentioned here is "self-moved machine that imitates the behaviour of humans or animals" [3].
    In BC 250, a water-powered clockwork, which can be considered as the first generation robot, was made by Ctesibius - at first most of the automations were toys and ornaments working with a simple clock-winder. - Later, these mechanisms were left themselves to toys for entertainment, which were mechanically programmed to perform only a certain task, imitating human and animal movements [4].
    In the 18th century, Droz produced a more complex automaton that could write and play the piano was known as the 'writer automaton’ [5].
    In the 19th century, Marie Jacquard invented the mechanical loom, which can be controlled numerically and the pattern to be woven with punched cards can be controlled [6]. Afterwards, the first remote control vehicles were developed by Nikola Tesla [7]. In 1928, a robot was invented in London, powered by an electric motor, electromagnets, pulleys, and wheels, limited to a fixed reach space [8]. In the 1930s, aircraft designers designed the autopilot for airplanes [9]. In the 1940s, Westinghouse created two robots that move completely independently in the horizontal plane [10]. In the same years, Shannon designed a mouse that could sense, see and react to its surroundings without human intervention, run a simple learning algorithm and solve mazes [11]. In 1953, a Japanese company Seiko developed a miniature robot that could assemble watch parts [12]. In 1954, George Devol invented a device that magnetically recorded electrical signals and then repeated this recording to control a machine. and Devol started to produce strong arms for the production line to General Motor's and thus the industrial robot revolution began [13].  In the 1960s, 'mobots' were invented, remotely controlled by humans with the aid of radio waves and cameras, to carry out chemical experiments and nuclear reactors in environments where people cannot be found [14]. In 1970, the Lunokhod 1 unmanned vehicle made an expedition to the surface of the moon [15]. In 1973, Richard Hohn invented a computer-controlled robot with a hydraulic movement mechanism that could lift up to 100kg [16].
    Today we live with robots helping people with housework, sweeping floors, walking dogs and lifting heavy items. More importantly, those cybernetic robots’ usage in society can provide valuable advantages, such as helping people with physical limitations; Robots that can play with children, prepare meals, serve, draw pictures and turn book pages.
   Likewise, the idea that more valuable work outputs can be obtained with robotic process automation in unmanned business areas is also that can seen as an advantage.
    In addition, operational robotic designs play an important role in both improving these processes and accelerating scientific research in environments that are not suitable for continuous operation of people, such as radiation environment, volcanic craters, space, underwater environments, toxic waste treatment centres, mining and mine clearance.
    Surgical interventions with the help of surgical robots to points that cannot be reached by human intervention in the field of medicine. These surgical robots, which are used in surgeries performed by experienced surgeons to patients who they are thousands of kilometres away is that other important benefits of robotics.
    On the other hand, the concerns about unemployment created by the use of robots in society are increasing day by day. The disadvantage of this is that there may be a decrease in consumption due to the increase in unemployment. As a result, imbalances between consumption and production may be serious deterioration in the supply-demand balance and may cause the annihilation of companies. There may also be deteriorations in the public coffers as a result of increased allowances due to unemployment. Thus, that can trigger the onset of economic crises [17], [18].

    II. CONCLUSION & RECOMENDATIONS
The use of robots can provide great advantages in environments where working conditions are difficult, and people cannot be present all the time. At the same time, it is possible to say that the use of robots in the field of medicine and health provides great benefits to people and is necessary.
 In this sense, what are the things that make life easier and the areas that provide comfort. It should be well evaluated based on the thought that every human being has no equal as an individual.
However, it is critical that the risk analysis be done correctly and the applicable ethical rules are clearly revealed for employment problems caused by robots.






